article.description:
LaQuanda Barksdale, playing her 12th game with a broken finger, completed a three-point play with 15.2 seconds
left to help the Portland Fire to a 68-64 victory over the
Cleveland Rockers on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Fire match team record with fourth straight win
article.linkText: Still missing Stiles, Fire roar to fourth straight win
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- LaQuanda Barksdale, playing her 12th game with
a broken finger, completed a three-point play with 15.2 seconds
left to help the Portland Fire to a 68-64 victory over the
Cleveland Rockers on Tuesday night.

	   "LaQuanda is what this team is about, battling through
adversity,'' Fire coach Linda Hargrove said. "She's going to have
surgery Friday and we're going to end up losing her.''

	   Barksdale scored on an offensive rebound, was fouled, and made
the free throw to give Portland (8-8) a 64-62 lead. The Fire
overcame an 11-point deficit for their fourth straight win,
matching a team record set last season.

	   The last three wins have come without injured Jackie Stiles. The
2001 rookie of the year is on the injured list with bursitis in her
right heel.

	   "We've had to piece together a team all year,'' Hargrove said.
"We feel we have the best depth in the league, though. Half our
points tend to come from players off the bench.''

	   The Fire's reserves outscored Cleveland's 30-6.

	   Starting guard Ukari Figgs scored 16 points to lead Portland.
She hit her first five shots, including four 3-pointers.

	   "My teammates just found me for open looks,'' Figgs said. "We
passed the ball well.''

	   Figgs, the WNBA's free-throw percentage leader, made two from
the line with 7.3 seconds left for a 66-62 lead. She is 42-for-44
this year from the line.

	   Penny Taylor scored on a putback with 1.2 seconds left for
Cleveland to make it 66-64 and Barksdale made two more free throws
with less than a second to play for the final margin.

	   "The key was our inability to rebound,'' Rockers coach Dan
Hughes said.

	   Portland's final four field goals all followed offensive
rebounds.

	   Merlakia Jones led Cleveland (6-8) with 18 points. Taylor scored
14 and Chasity Melvin and Ann Wauters had 13 apiece for the
Rockers, who lost at home for the third time after leading by
double digits. Cleveland is 4-5 at Gund Arena after going 14-2 at
home last year.

	   The Rockers hit eight of their first nine shots and used a 10-0
run to lead 19-9. Cleveland led at the break 35-26.

	   Jones had 10 points on 5-of-7 shooting in the first half as the
Rockers' starters outscored Portland's 33-16.

	   The Fire finally took their first lead at 42-41 with 14:47 to
play when Figgs hit her fourth 3-pointer to cap a 16-6 run.

	   "They came out very aggressively and we did not react well,''
Hughes said. "In the first half, we did a better job of spreading
the floor, then we became impatient.''

	   DeMya Walker and Sylvia Crawley each scored 10 points for
Portland.

	   Cleveland point guard Jennifer Rizzotti was put on the injured
list before the game with a sprained right ankle. Rookie Brandi
McCain started at point guard and did not score in 21 minutes with
two assists and five turnovers.

	   "Taking care of the ball is a big factor,'' said Rockers
reserve point guard Tricia Bader-Binford, who went scoreless with
two assists in 11 minutes. "We got too antsy and it played right
into their hands.''
